  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity internationally. It involves the process of converting funds obtained from illegal activities into apparently legitimate money or other assets. Most countries have laws and regulations that make money laundering a criminal offense, often with severe penalties. The global effort to combat money laundering is coordinated by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets international standards to prevent this illegal activity. In China, for example, the Anti-Money Laundering Law, along with related regulations and guidelines, strictly prohibits money laundering and outlines the legal responsibilities of financial institutions and other entities to detect and report money laundering activities. The Chinese government is committed to maintaining the integrity of its financial system and actively participates in international cooperation to combat money laundering and related crimes.",
